<h3>The Question</h3>
<p>
    Decision <a href="/backlog/012-gap-5-webidentity-project/">#012</a> settled <em>what</em>
    <code>webidentity</code> is — a project owning one <code>credential-acquisition</code> protocol, families as
    a request dimension, identity feeding the <a href="/protocols/guard/">Guard</a> access-gate — and shipped the
    thin UX intent (<a href="/backlog/482-web-identity-thin-intent-mediation-credential-request-auth-s/">#482</a>).
    It did <strong>not</strong> settle <em>how to build</em> the deferred protocol. This survey, per design-first
    step&nbsp;1, grounds the three build-level forks in
    <a href="/backlog/496-webidentity-build-design-credential-acquisition-protocol-con/">#496</a> (which blocks the
    deferred epic <a href="/backlog/483-webidentity-project-credential-acquisition-protocol-deferred/">#483</a>):
    the <strong>provider-seam contract shape</strong>, the protocol's <strong>lifecycle scope</strong>, and whether
    a <strong>Configurator domain</strong> is in-scope. The external identity landscape is already covered by the
    <a href="/research/web-identity-project/">Web Identity Project</a> survey; the new ground is the full
    <code>CredentialsContainer</code> method surface and the internal provider-seam precedent.
</p>

<h3>Recommendation (for #496)</h3>
<p>
    <em>Ratified (2026-06-13): all three defaults, with one override — the protocol was renamed
    <code>credential-acquisition</code> → <code>credential-management</code> once the member set grew past
    get-only to the full Credential Management API surface (request + enrollment + sign-out). This survey uses the
    working name <code>credential-acquisition</code> throughout.</em>
</p>
<ol>
    <li><strong>One <code>CustomCredentialProvider</code> contract, registry-resolved per requested family</strong>
        (<code>default → project override → custom plug</code>, the Guard pattern). Default provider = native
        <code>navigator.credentials</code> passthrough; a <strong>mock in-memory provider</strong> ships for
        server-less conformance. Ceremony libraries (SimpleWebAuthn/Hanko) are swappable plugs.</li>
    <li><strong>Lifecycle modelled as protocol members</strong> — <code>credential-request</code> (get, all
        families), <code>credential-enrollment</code> (create/store, passkey + password),
        <code>session-mediation</code> (preventSilentAccess sign-out, origin-global) — not a flat contract that
        forces get-only families to stub methods. <em>(Ratified as <code>credential-management</code> — see note above.)</em></li>
    <li><strong>Omit the Configurator domain</strong> from this build; technical defaults ride the provider
        registry + config-flavors. Carve a plateau-app domain only if a real ceremony-authoring need emerges.</li>
</ol>

<h3>Finding 1 — the credential lifecycle is four methods, with asymmetric per-family support</h3>
<p>
    <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/CredentialsContainer"><code>navigator.credentials</code></a>
    exposes <strong>four</strong> methods, not one — and support is <strong>asymmetric by family</strong>:
</p>
<ul>
    <li><strong><code>get()</code></strong> — acquisition / authentication. Supported by <em>all</em> families
        (password, passkey, FedCM, digital).</li>
    <li><strong><code>create()</code></strong> — enrollment / registration. <em>Only</em> passkey (a new
        <code>PublicKeyCredential</code>) and password. FedCM and Digital Credentials are <strong>get-only</strong>
        — enrollment happens off-platform at the IdP / wallet issuer.</li>
    <li><strong><code>store()</code></strong> — persist after auth. <em>Only</em> password (the authenticator
        self-stores passkeys).</li>
    <li><strong><code>preventSilentAccess()</code></strong> — sign-out: an origin-global flag that blocks
        automatic re-login on the next visit.</li>
</ul>
<p>
    The load-bearing consequence: a protocol fixing a single flat "credential" contract would force the get-only
    families to stub out <code>create</code>/<code>store</code>. This is exactly the shape
    <a href="/protocols/guard/">Guard</a> solved with <strong>members</strong> — <em>"deny-outcomes are NOT
    unified; each member owns its own family"</em> — which is why Fork&nbsp;2 recommends
    <code>credential-request</code> / <code>credential-enrollment</code> / <code>session-mediation</code> members,
    each declaring the families it supports.
</p>

<h3>Finding 2 — every WE project owns a protocol with one swappable <code>CustomXProvider</code> seam</h3>
<p>
    <code>CustomCredentialProvider</code> is not greenfield. The constellation's pattern is uniform: a project owns
    <strong>one</strong> protocol fixing <strong>one</strong> seam resolved by a swappable provider, native-first
    default → project override → custom plug:
</p>
<ul>
    <li><a href="/protocols/guard/">Guard</a> — <code>CustomGuardProvider</code>, <em>async, server-authoritative
        (the front-end is a UX mirror, never enforcement), revocable</em>. The <strong>identical</strong> trust
        boundary identity carries: the browser only <em>gathers</em> a credential the server then verifies.</li>
    <li>Lifecycle — <code>CustomLifecycleProvider</code> registry; delegates authorization to Guard and persistence
        to its own concern.</li>
    <li>Validation (<code>CustomValidation</code>), Change Tracking (<code>CustomChangeStrategy</code>, per-scope
        registry), Localization (<code>CustomTranslationProvider</code>), Anchor Positioning
        (<code>CustomPositioner</code>), Render Strategy (<code>CustomRenderStrategy</code>).</li>
</ul>
<p>
    So the only genuinely open design is the contract's <em>method set</em> (Finding&nbsp;1's lifecycle) and how the
    demo stays server-less (Finding&nbsp;3) — not the registry/resolution mechanics, which are precedent.
</p>

<h3>Finding 3 — server-less demoability needs a mock provider (also doctrine)</h3>
<p>
    Both #012 and #483 deferred <em>because</em> "ceremonies need real server counterparts to demo." The provider
    seam dissolves this: ship a native-first default (<code>navigator.credentials</code> passthrough) <strong>plus
    a mock/in-memory conformance provider</strong> returning a canned typed credential with no RP server, so every
    fixture and demo runs offline. Real RP-backed providers (a SimpleWebAuthn server harness) become an opt-in
    adapter demo later, not a precondition. This native-first-default + opt-in-adapter layering is what makes the
    eventual build sliceable with <em>every slice demoable</em> — the exact condition the split analysis flagged as
    failing.
</p>

<h3>Finding 4 — "Configurator domain" is separable and possibly omittable</h3>
<p>
    #012 lumped "the full protocol + provider contract + Configurator domain" into one deferral. But the
    Configurator is a <strong>plateau-app</strong> (product-layer) concern, and the platform already has a
    <strong>config-flavors</strong> mechanism for technical defaults — the Auto-Define-Strategy protocol states
    <em>"the tool carries no default; the default-strategy selection comes from the platform config a project
    extends, shipped in flavors."</em> So a technical mediation/provider default rides config-flavors without a
    bespoke Configurator domain. Whether identity warrants its own guided ceremony-config surface is a real,
    separable question — not automatically in-scope for the standard-layer build.
</p>

